http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Kochi/Third-Eye-to-scan-State-roads-for-offences/article13987855.ece

Third Eye, a camouflage enforcement operation successfully undertaken by the Ernakulam Regional Transport Office enlisting members of the civic society, is all set to be emulated across the State.An announcement in this regard is likely at the valedictory function of the almost a fortnight-long project to be held at the seminar complex of the Cochin University of Science and Technology (Cusat) on Friday.K.S. Radhakrishnan, chairman of the Supreme Court-appointed Road Safety Commission, will inaugurate the function to be presided over by Transport Minister Thiruvanchoor Radhakrishnan.NSS volunteersThe project involved the deployment of 60 National Service Scheme volunteers of Cusat on 13 accident prone roads in the city with the task of photographing traffic violations.The Motor Vehicle Department (MVD) is also likely to take up with the apex court-appointed committee the need for the State government to frame rules to empower the MVD officials according to Section 213 (5) of the Central Motor Vehicles Act to strengthen enforcement.The Act empowers an officer of the department to search any premises or vehicle if an offence under the Act is committed by a person.It also sates that any such search without a warrant can be conducted only by an official of the rank of a Gazetted officer. If the offence can be punished with fine, the search should not be made after sunset and before sunrise. If the search is made without a warrant, the Gazetted Officer should write the reason for not obtaining a warrant and report to his immediate superior.It further states that the officer can examine any person, demand the production of any register or document and take statements. The official can seize or take copies of any registers, documents and launch prosecutions in respect of any offence under this Act and to take a bond for ensuring the attendance of the offender before any court.